accredited investors have the opportunity to earn income and diversify thei=
r portfolio without the headache and hassle of buying a property, renting i=
t out, or maintaining it.
The Fusion Race
Packy McCormick x Rahul Rana
Two weeks ago, a startup funded and chaired by Sam Altman announced a big p=
artnership with Microsoft. This time, instead of investing in Sam=E2=80=99s=
 brain, Microsoft committed to buying his power.
Specifically, according to the press release [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/d56f78d2-37fc-42b6-b281-1ede29465e25?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
Helion Energy (Helion) today announced an agreement to provide Microsoft el=
ectricity from its first fusion power plant. The plant is expected to be on=
line by 2028 and will target power generation of 50 MW or greater after a 1=
-year ramp up period. The planned operational date for this first of its ki=
nd facility is significantly sooner than typical projections for deployment=
 of commercial fusion power.
While Sam Altman selling to Microsoft invites obvious OpenAI [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/29cf6a24-1a99-4901-80ee-6c5a62f9aa1e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] comparisons, the better an=
alogy may be to one of the companies founded by Sam=E2=80=99s erstwhile Ope=
nAI co-founder: SpaceX.=C2=A0
Like SpaceX, Helion [ https://substack.com/redirect/569d0179-9e66-4b71-be3a=
-e3aedcd389fb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] set an absurdly aggressive timeline in an industry not recently kno=
wn for its speed. Like SpaceX, Helion is the beneficiary of billions of dol=
lars and decades=E2=80=99 worth of government-funded research, of global co=
mpetition and cooperation in the pursuit of civilization-scale goals.=C2=A0
And like SpaceX, Helion may mark a turning point in one of the coming decad=
es=E2=80=99 most consequential industries, the baton handoff from the measu=
red and fundamental world of government and academia into the chaos and has=
te of the market.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re using Helion liberally here. We don=E2=80=99t know who will w=
in Fusion Race 2.0, and this isn=E2=80=99t a winner-take-all market. But He=
lion is a worthy stand-in for the growing number of privately funded fusion=
 companies racing to bring the power of the stars to the earth=E2=80=99s el=
ectric grid, economically.=C2=A0
Imagine a bizarro relay marathon in which one runner carries the baton for =
the first 26.0 miles, opens up a backpack full of batons, and hands them ou=
t liberally to a waiting horde of sprinters to dash all-out for the final 0=
=2E2 miles. That=E2=80=99s the best analog=
y we can come up with for this mome=
nt in the Fusion Race.=C2=A0
Global governments are the marathon runner. From the race to develop thermo=
nuclear weapons after World War II, to the $22 billion, 50+ year cooperativ=
e ITER [ https://substack.com/redirect/4e72caac-c6dd-49ac-9495-eb54bab1f978=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] react=
or currently being built in France, to the National Ignition Facility=E2=80=
=99s ignition achievement in December 2022 [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
d28495bc-46c6-42e7-9add-4a93ee76e349?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], governments have led fusion research effort=
s for the better part of eight decades.=C2=A0
The world=E2=80=99s governments have run a well-paced marathon, producing s=
omething akin to a Moore=E2=80=99s Law in fusion for half a century. The tr=
iple product =E2=80=93 of density, temperature, and time =E2=80=93 is the f=
igure-of-merit in fusion, and it doubled every 1.8 years from the late 1950=
s through the early 2000s, as one type of reactor - tokamaks, a form of mag=
netic confinement fusion (MCF) - got larger and more powerful.=C2=A0
In December, scientists at the government-funded National Ignition Facility=
 (NIF) at Lawrence Livermore made headlines when they achieved fusion ignit=
ion, or scientific energy breakeven, for the first time in a controlled env=
ironment That is, they got more energy out of the fusion reaction than they=
 spent on the laser energy used to drive it. The NIF used a different appro=
ach: inertial confinement fusion (ICF).=C2=A0
The world rejoiced =E2=80=93 fusion energy is possible! =E2=80=93 and then =
sobered up =E2=80=93 it was like a AA battery=E2=80=99s worth of energy and=
, experts pointed out, commercial-scale fusion power might not arrive for d=
ecades.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the joke in fusion, that fusion power is =E2=80=9Calways 30 =
years away.=E2=80=9D Funny joke, to be sure, but it may no longer be true.=
=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re at the handoff point, from private to public, thanks to impro=
ving compute and machine learning, better magnets and materials, the divers=
e range of technical approaches that are finally becoming feasible, and dra=
matically increased capital availability for startups.=C2=A0
Companies like Helion, Commonwealth Fusion Systems, TAE Technologies, Gener=
al Fusion, and Zap Energy are the sprinters. Armed with $5 billion in fundi=
ng, most of which has come in just the past two years, and decades worth of=
 research made feasible by new tools, fusion startups are locked in a mad d=
ash to the finish in what might be called Fusion Race 2.0. At the end stand=
s commercial fusion and a healthy chunk of the $15 trillion global energy m=
arket.=C2=A0
Magic can happen in this public-to-private handoff. After languishing for d=
ecades post-Moon Landing, SpaceX revitalized the space economy [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/350fa65a-e093-4368-b7ec-259b64d9cd52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and enabled a constellat=
ion of new businesses driven by both a sense of adventure and a profit moti=
ve. The commercialization of space pulled in timelines for such sci-fi visi=
ons as asteroid mining, space manufacturing, space hotels, and even Mars ha=
bitation by decades.=C2=A0
We don=E2=80=99t pretend to know who the SpaceX of fusion will be =E2=80=93=
 in fact, it may be a confluence of factors more than any one company that =
unlocks the fusion economy =E2=80=93 but we suspect that we=E2=80=99re at a=
 similar point in fusion=E2=80=99s evolution.=C2=A0
Commercial fusion may power (some of) our homes within the decade.=C2=A0
As humanity embarks on this leg of one of our most important journeys, we t=
hought it would be useful to put together a little primer on what=E2=80=99s=
 at stake, how fusion works, where it=E2=80=99s been, and where we=E2=80=99=
re heading. We=E2=80=99ll do that today by covering:
Why is Fusion Important?
How Fusion Works
A Brief History of Fusion
Plasma Progress
Fusion Race 2.0
The Fusion Startup Landscape
Energy Too Cheap to Meter, Too Soon to Believe=C2=A0=C2=A0
To start, let=E2=80=99s all get on the same page about why fusion is import=
ant in the first place.
Why is Fusion Important?=C2=A0
According to Greek mythology, Prometheus defied the gods by stealing fire a=
nd bestowing it upon humanity. Humans harnessed the power of fire to constr=
uct magnificent cities and propel the growth of their civilization.
It=E2=80=99s such an alluring myth that we still use it as a shorthand for =
human ambition, innovation, and the quest for knowledge in the face of dang=
er to this day.=C2=A0
Fusion is the Promethean myth brought to life, minus the liver-eating Cauca=
sian Eagle [ https://substack.com/redirect/31e9de6b-ee05-4b53-9c54-28b06e4e=
1e72?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (=
we hope). It=E2=80=99s the engine that powers the stars. By wresting the se=
cret of unlimited energy production from the heavens, humanity may once aga=
in construct wonders in the physical world and propel the growth of our civ=
ilization.=C2=A0
A few years ago, it might have been controversial to argue that the world s=
hould use more energy. The climate argument thrusted in the opposite direct=
ion =E2=80=93 consume less energy and transition whatever energy we still n=
eed to use to clean, renewable sources like solar and wind. Degrowth is a l=
osing argument, and thankfully, it is in the process of being replaced by a=
 more optimistic one: the call for energy superabundance.
Instead of consuming less energy, this argument goes, we should produce uni=
maginable amounts of clean energy from all of the sources we can: solar, wi=
nd, geothermal, nuclear fission, and one day, fusion. With practically unli=
mited cheap energy, we=E2=80=99ll be able to suck CO2 out of the air, mitig=
ate the effects of climate change, and have enough left over to meaningfull=
y improve the quality of life for billions of people around the world. We l=
ike this argument.
Energy use is the bound of civilization. If you increase it, civilization g=
rows and progresses. If you limit it, civilization stagnates. If you dimini=
sh it, civilization crumbles. Energy is the most fundamental determinant of=
 a society=E2=80=99s success. It feeds us, houses us, wins wars, powers tec=
hnology, and dictates policy. Even money is a mere proxy for energy.=C2=A0
More energy lifts all boats. Numerous studies have found a long-run, direct=
, causal, and bidirectional [ https://substack.com/redirect/2cb39cde-fa4c-4=
c3c-b3ad-365c7d96fc20?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] relationship between energy consumption and economic growth=
=2E Researchers found [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/2cb39cde-fa4c-4c3c-b3ad=
-365c7d96fc20?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] that a 1% increase in real GDP per capita increases total energy co=
nsumption by 0.6%. It works the other way, too [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/61e63101-2e77-48f6-956b-979b1f72f979?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94a 0.9% increase in electricity u=
se in OECD countries led to a 1.7% increase in GDP. For non=E2=80=93OECD co=
untries, a 2% annual increase in electricity use increases GDP by 3.8%. =C2=
=A0
Simply put, more energy means more progress, and vice versa, across the boa=
rd. More energy, and the physical abundance it brings, would spur growth wi=
thout accelerating inequality.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re with us that more energy consumption is a good thing, the=
n we have good news: humans are consuming more energy than ever before.=C2=
=A0
The challenge, of course, is that the sources of energy humanity has ridden=
 to such great heights also happen to be bad for the environment. The CO2, =
methane, and other greenhouse gasses emitted when they=E2=80=99re burned po=
se an existential risk to the planet. Even if they didn=E2=80=99t harm the =
environment, fossil fuels will eventually run out, even if we find increasi=
ngly clever ways to dig them up.=C2=A0
So the goal is to not just replace fossil fuels with cleaner energy sources=
, but to produce oodles and oodles of clean, abundant energy, multiples mor=
e than we produce and consume today.=C2=A0
For much, much more =E2=80=94 including how we=E2=80=99ll produce all that =
clean energy, a history of fusion, and an overview of the startups racing t=
o achieve ignition=E2=80=A6
If this button breaks, you can find the full essay at Not Boring [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/411ed924-9056-4585-a810-6214af5c01ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=20
Thanks to Rahul [ https://substack.com/redirect/c94964b8-6835-495f-aee4-b8b=
5293b9a55?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for the collaboration and to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/44f058=
6e-54ac-4f1d-8363-88f0f0675c82?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox a couple =
times later this week =F0=9F=91=80
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

